You are a security researcher analyzing Apache MyFaces JSF ViewState encryption code.

Below is the cryptography Apache MyFaces Core 1.2.8 uses to protect the client-side JSF ViewState (CVE-2010-2057). StateUtils encrypts the serialized view state with a configured symmetric cipher and -- critically -- there is NO Message Authentication Code: encrypt() and decrypt() simply delegate to a shared symmetric() helper that performs Cipher.doFinal(). When the cipher is configured as AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding, decryption reveals PKCS#7 padding validity (a wrapped BadPaddingException, distinguishable from success). MyFaces base64-encodes the result and stores it as the ViewState:

**File: StateUtils.java (Apache MyFaces shared-impl 3.0.7, shipped in Core 1.2.8)**
```java
    public static byte[] encrypt(byte[] insecure, ExternalContext ctx)
    {
        return symmetric(insecure, ctx, Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE);
    }

    public static byte[] decrypt(byte[] secure, ExternalContext ctx)
    {
        return symmetric(secure, ctx, Cipher.DECRYPT_MODE);
    }

    private static byte[] symmetric(byte[] data, SecretKey secretKey,
            String algorithm, String algorithmParams, byte[] iv, int mode){

        try
        {
            // keep local to avoid threading issue
            Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(algorithm + "/"
                    + algorithmParams);
            if (iv != null)
            {
                IvParameterSpec ivSpec = new IvParameterSpec(iv);
                cipher.init(mode, secretKey, ivSpec);
            }
            else
            {
                cipher.init(mode, secretKey);
            }

            if (log.isDebugEnabled())
            {

                String action = mode == Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE ? "encrypting"
                        : "decrypting";

                log.debug(action + " w/ " + algorithm + "/" + algorithmParams);
            }

            return cipher.doFinal(data);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            throw new FacesException(e);
        }

    }
```
On Restore View, reconstruct() base64-decodes the ViewState and calls decrypt(); a decryption failure (including the PKCS#7 padding failure raised by the cipher) surfaces as a FacesException, distinguishable from a successful restore. There is NO integrity check, so an attacker can tamper with the ViewState and use the valid/invalid response as a classic Vaudenay CBC padding oracle -- recovering plaintext (and forging view state) without knowing the key.

